{
  "doc_id": "55456",
  "text": "A third strand of research has focused on specific nutrient and non-nutrient components of foods. Dietary antioxidants such as b-carotene, Zn, Se, vitamin C and vitamin E have been shown to be associated with lower levels of disease-related markers of inflammation in adulthood (26 -30) and even earlier in life, in adolescence [CITATION_1] . Non-nutritive polyphenolic compounds such as flavonoids, present in plant-based foods and drinks, particularly fruit, vegetables, tea, red wine and cocoa, have significant antioxidant and anti-inflammatory activity [CITATION_2] , and have emerged in recent years as an important component in the relationship between diet and inflammation (33 -38) and with cardiovascular health [CITATION_3] . It is unclear whether specific food components such as antioxidants and flavonoids are responsible for the apparent protective role of nutrient-dense dietary patterns and foods.",
